text: Simulate example data following paper: Kim, Jae Kwang, Zhonglei Wang. ‚ÄúSampling techniques big data analysis.‚Äù International Statistical Review 87 (2019): S177-S191 [section 5.2] Declare svydesign object survey package Estimate population mean y1 based doubly robust estimator using IPW calibration constraints. Results Mass imputation estimator Results Inverse probability weighting estimator Results
code: library(survey) library(nonprobsvy)  set.seed(1234567890) N <- 1e6 ## 1000000 n <- 1000 x1 <- rnorm(n = N, mean = 1, sd = 1) x2 <- rexp(n = N, rate = 1) epsilon <- rnorm(n = N) # rnorm(N) y1 <- 1 + x1 + x2 + epsilon y2 <- 0.5*(x1 - 0.5)^2 + x2 + epsilon p1 <- exp(x2)/(1+exp(x2)) p2 <- exp(-0.5+0.5*(x2-2)^2)/(1+exp(-0.5+0.5*(x2-2)^2)) flag_bd1 <- rbinom(n = N, size = 1, prob = p1) flag_srs <- as.numeric(1:N %in% sample(1:N, size = n)) base_w_srs <- N/n population <- data.frame(x1,x2,y1,y2,p1,p2,base_w_srs, flag_bd1, flag_srs) base_w_bd <- N/sum(population$flag_bd1) sample_prob <- svydesign(ids= ~1, weights = ~ base_w_srs,                           data = subset(population, flag_srs == 1)) result_dr <- nonprob(   selection = ~ x2,   outcome = y1 ~ x1 + x2,   data = subset(population, flag_bd1 == 1),   svydesign = sample_prob ) summary(result_dr) #>  #> Call: #> nonprob(data = subset(population, flag_bd1 == 1), selection = ~x2,  #>     outcome = y1 ~ x1 + x2, svydesign = sample_prob) #>  #> ------------------------- #> Estimated population mean: 2.95 with overall std.err of: 0.04195 #> And std.err for nonprobability and probability samples being respectively: #> 0.000783 and 0.04195 #>  #> 95% Confidence inverval for popualtion mean: #>    lower_bound upper_bound #> y1    2.867789     3.03224 #>  #>  #> Based on: Doubly-Robust method #> For a population of estimate size: 1025063 #> Obtained on a nonprobability sample of size: 693011 #> With an auxiliary probability sample of size: 1000 #> ------------------------- #>  #> Regression coefficients: #> ----------------------- #> For glm regression on outcome variable: #>             Estimate Std. what: Inference with the non-probability survey samples ‚Äî nonprob
title: Inference with the non-probability survey samples ‚Äî nonprob
text: nonprob fits model inference based non-probability surveys (including big data) using various methods. function allows estimate population mean access reference probability sample, well sums means covariates. package implements state---art approaches recently proposed literature: Chen et al. (2020), Yang et al. (2020), Wu (2022) uses Lumley 2004 survey package inference. provides propensity score weighting (e.g. calibration constraints), mass imputation (e.g. nearest neighbour) doubly robust estimators take account minimisation asymptotic bias population mean estimators variable selection. package uses survey package functionality probability sample available.

title: Inference with the non-probability survey samples ‚Äî nonprob
text: data data.frame data non-probability sample. selection formula, selection (propensity) equation. outcome formula, outcome equation. target formula target variables. svydesign optional svydesign object (survey package) containing probability sample design weights. pop_totals optional named vector population totals covariates. pop_means optional named vector population means covariates. pop_size optional double population size. method_selection character method propensity scores estimation. method_outcome character method response variable estimation. family_outcome character string describing error distribution link function used model. Default "gaussian". Currently supports: gaussian identity link, poisson binomial. subset optional vector specifying subset observations used fitting process. strata optional vector specifying strata. weights optional vector prior weights used fitting process. NULL numeric vector. assumed vector contains frequency analytic weights. na_action function indicates happen data contain NAs. control_selection list indicating parameters use fitting selection model propensity scores. control_outcome list indicating parameters use fitting model outcome variable. control_inference list indicating parameters use inference based probability non-probability samples, contains parameters estimation method variance method. start_selection optional vector starting values parameters selection equation. start_outcome optional vector starting values parameters outcome equation. verbose verbose, numeric. x Logical value indicating whether return model matrix covariates part output. y Logical value indicating whether return vector outcome variable part output. se Logical value indicating whether calculate return standard error estimated mean. ... Additional, optional arguments.

code: # \donttest{ # generate data based on Doubly Robust Inference With Non-probability Survey Samples (2021) # Yilin Chen , Pengfei Li & Changbao Wu library(sampling) #>  #> Attaching package: ‚Äòsampling‚Äô #> The following objects are masked from ‚Äòpackage:survival‚Äô: #>  #>     cluster, strata set.seed(123) # sizes of population and probability sample N <- 20000 # population n_b <- 1000 # probability # data z1 <- rbinom(N, 1, 0.7) z2 <- runif(N, 0, 2) z3 <- rexp(N, 1) z4 <- rchisq(N, 4)  # covariates x1 <- z1 x2 <- z2 + 0.3 * z2 x3 <- z3 + 0.2 * (z1 + z2) x4 <- z4 + 0.1 * (z1 + z2 + z3) epsilon <- rnorm(N) sigma_30 <- 10.4 sigma_50 <- 5.2 sigma_80 <- 2.4  # response variables y30 <- 2 + x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + sigma_30 * epsilon y50 <- 2 + x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + sigma_50 * epsilon y80 <- 2 + x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 + sigma_80 * epsilon  # population sim_data <- data.frame(y30, y50, y80, x1, x2, x3, x4) ## propensity score model for non-probability sample (sum to 1000) eta <- -4.461 + 0.1 * x1 + 0.2 * x2 + 0.1 * x3 + 0.2 * x4 rho <- plogis(eta)  # inclusion probabilities for probability sample z_prob <- x3 + 0.2051 sim_data$p_prob <- inclusionprobabilities(z_prob, n = n_b)  # data sim_data$flag_nonprob <- UPpoisson(rho) ## sampling nonprob sim_data$flag_prob <- UPpoisson(sim_data$p_prob) ## sampling prob nonprob_df <- subset(sim_data, flag_nonprob == 1) ## non-probability sample svyprob <- svydesign(   ids = ~1, probs = ~p_prob,   data = subset(sim_data, flag_prob == 1),   pps = "brewer" ) ## probability sample  ## mass imputation estimator MI_res <- nonprob(   outcome = y80 ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4,   data = nonprob_df,   svydesign = svyprob ) summary(MI_res) #>  #> Call: #> nonprob(data = nonprob_df, outcome = y80 ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4,  #>     svydesign = svyprob) #>  #> ------------------------- #> Estimated population mean: 9.518 with overall std.err of: 0.151 #> And std.err for nonprobability and probability samples being respectively: #> 0.08679 and 0.1236 #>  #> 95% Confidence inverval for popualtion mean: #>     lower_bound upper_bound #> y80    9.222349    9.814346 #>  #>  #> Based on: Mass Imputation method #> For a population of estimate size: 21631.63 #> Obtained on a nonprobability sample of size: 1032 #> With an auxiliary probability sample of size: 1044 #> ------------------------- #>  #> Regression coefficients: #> ----------------------- #> For glm regression on outcome variable: #>             Estimate Std.
